pair_address: Unique id for this token market (ex sol-doge), a pair is where you trade one specific token for another specific token
signature: The identifier for the transaction that created this pair
token_address: The identifier for the memecoin token that is traded on this pair (the other token in the pair is always solana)
token_decimals: Number of percision points after the decimal point for the token
pair_sol_account: The account containing the solana liquidity for the pairs constant product curve
pair_token_account: The account containing the memecoin token liquidity for the pairs constant product curve
protocol: The type of token market each is slightly different and focused on different types of markets and has different target consumers
created_at: Time the pair was first created
website: For the memecoin token from the metadata
twitter: For the memecoin token from the metadata
telegram: For the memecoin token from the metadata
discord: For the memecoin token from the metadata
mint_authority: The account that is allowed to create more of the memecoin in this pair
open_trading: The time that trading is allowed to start (defined by pair creator and can be far in the past)
deployer_address: The account address of the pair creator
supply: The total supply of the memecoin in this pair
initial_liquidity_sol: The starting liquidity of solana for the constant product curve
initial_liquidity_token: The starting liquidity of memecoin token for the constant product curve
top_10_holders: Percent of memecoin tokens held by top 10 accounts (not useful as not historical)
lp_burned: The percentage of the memecoin token liquidity in the pair that cannot be taken out (not very useful as not historical)
updated_at: The last time current stats were updated (not very useful as not historical)
freeze_authority: The account that can stop trading on the pair (empty or null when no one has this ability)
extra: Either null or an object with data about migration between different protocols (like moving pump to raydium) (will be useful info but I will explain in a meeting, essentially it provides sub categories for the 'protocol' field)
